      Buyout debt
   =20
 =20
=E2=80=9CWall Street Faces Billion-Dollar Losses on Sinking Buyout Debt,=E2=
=80=9D says  this Bloomberg News article, and it doesn=E2=80=99t even menti=
on Twitter!Investment bankers in the US and Europe are bracing for potentia=
lly billions of dollars in total losses on big-ticket leveraged buyouts as =
they struggle to offload risky corporate debt that=E2=80=99s plunging in va=
lue amid a sweeping market selloff. ...Underwriters on both sides of the At=
lantic are now sitting on an estimated $80 billion of commitments backing l=
everaged buyouts that will be difficult to sell in a market for junk debt t=
hat is effectively frozen. While that=E2=80=99s a modest undertaking compar=
ed to the more than $200 billion stockpile heading into the 2008 crisis, th=
e worry is that writedowns will grow as rates rise, acting as a drag on ear=
nings. =E2=80=A6Last week Deutsche Bank AG showed its peers the scale of th=
e problem as it sold high-yield bonds backing the buyout of packaging firm =
Intertape Polymer Group Inc. at just 82 cents on the dollar, one of the ste=
epest discounts on a new junk-bond issue in two decades.=C2=A0Ditto for Cre=
dit Suisse. It finalized the sale this week of an offering backing Lone Sta=
r Funds=E2=80=99 acquisition of chemicals distribution company Manuchar NV =
at the largest discount in a decade for the European market: 86 cents on th=
e euro. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CBanks agreed to finance deals months ago and we=
=E2=80=99ve had a massive shift in expectations,=E2=80=9D said Nichole Hamm=
ond, a senior portfolio manager at Angel Oak Capital Advisors. =E2=80=9CThe=
 uncertain economic backdrop is causing investors to be much more selective=
 and they want to be paid more for the risks they are taking.=E2=80=9DThis =
is related to the phenomenon we have  talked about  recently where sometime=
s buyers sign merger agreements, agreeing to buy companies for cash, in a b=
oom, and then the bust happens before the merger closes, and the price of t=
he merger seems too high. (Sometimes the buyer then manages to renegotiate =
the deal.) If you agree to=C2=A0finance a deal at, like, eight times earnin=
gs with a 9% interest-rate cap, and then the market crashes and that debt r=
equires a 13% yield, then you will end up selling it at 82 cents on the dol=
lar, oops.It is in a sense a worse problem for the banks than it is for the=
 buyers, though, because the buyers generally=C2=A0intend=C2=A0to own the c=
ompanies for a long time. If you sign a deal to buy a company and the marke=
t crashes before the deal closes, that is not=C2=A0so=C2=A0different from t=
he market crashing=C2=A0after the deal closes. You might get cold feet, but=
 you wanted to buy this company for some sort of long-term strategic reason=
, and presumably the market cycle doesn=E2=80=99t change that too much.But =
the banks do=C2=A0not intend to own the buyout debt: They write commitment =
letters promising to buy the debt if no one else will, and then they get to=
 work selling it to investors. They are in the moving business, not the sto=
rage business, when it comes to this sort of debt; if the crash had come ju=
st a bit later they=E2=80=99d have sold it off at par and collected their f=
ees. Of course then they=E2=80=99d have moved on to do other deals, which w=
ould get hung when the crash eventually came.
