<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Revlon</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every meme-stock story is about two th=
ings:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin:=
 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Memes, and</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Limits to arbitrage.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Sometimes the memes are what get things started, and the limits to=
 arbitrage are what keep=C2=A0the meme alive. A bunch of people on Reddit w=
ill decide that they like a stock because its chief executive officer does =
funny stuff online, and they=E2=80=99ll buy the=C2=A0stock and it=C2=A0will=
 go up, and hedge funds will say =E2=80=9Cthis stock is too high, we should=
 short it,=E2=80=9D but then they won=E2=80=99t because it is too hard to s=
hort the stock.=C2=A0Other times, though, the memes are=C2=A0<em>about=C2=
=A0</em>the limits to arbitrage. There will be some stock that is bad, and =
a lot of people will have shorted the stock, because it is bad, and then pe=
ople will go on Reddit and say =E2=80=9Ca lot of people are short this stoc=
k, short squeezes are fun, let=E2=80=99s do one,=E2=80=9D and they will and=
 it will become a meme stock. The short squeeze will be the meme. In a sens=
e, Reddit itself is a powerful limit to arbitrage.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Revlon Inc. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL=
2RhdGEvODg3OTIxLzAwMDExNDAzNjEyMjAyMzE4Mi9icmhjMTAwMzg3NTBfOGsuaHRt/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB37b5702a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">filed for bankruptcy</a> on the evening=
 of June 15. Its stock had closed at $2.25 that day. It closed at $8.14 yes=
terday, up 260% in the week since the bankruptcy filing, on enormous volume=
. Does this make sense? I mean, the short answer is =E2=80=9Cno,=E2=80=9D b=
ut here are some longer answers from Claire Ballentine and Jeremy Hill <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMjMvc2hvdWxkLWktY=
nV5LXJldmxvbi1yZXYtYmFua3J1cHQtY29zbWV0aWNzLWNvbXBhbnktaXMtbGF0ZXN0LW1lbWUt=
c3RvY2s_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7100dd0d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> at Bloomberg</a>:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The surge makes little sense to professional =
traders, and is also strangely incongruous with the broader market, where e=
verything from established companies to cryptocurrencies are getting crushe=
d amid concerns over inflation and a more aggressive Federal Reserve. At a =
time when easy money and outsized stock gains are fading from memory, the m=
ove shows how some retail traders, encouraged by Reddit forums, are still a=
ble to move markets.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s somewhat bizarre,=E2=80=9D said Bloomberg Intelligence analyst Phil=
 Brendel of Revlon=E2=80=99s rally. The company would need to be sold or ot=
herwise valued at more than $4 billion in order for stockholders to see a r=
ecovery, he said in an interview. Any windfall would have to repay Revlon=
=E2=80=99s debts plus accrued interest, as well as whatever the company bor=
rows to fund its bankruptcy, to say nothing of the pricey advisers who over=
see a restructuring.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And=
 Sujeet Indap <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2815=
4643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZjhhMTc5M2ItOTU4Ni00M2NkLTl=
lMzUtMDA2ZWRlNDg1OWMz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5dc4ed51" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">at FT Alph=
aville</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bottom line rem=
ains that Revlon, beyond its current cash crunch, remains overlevered (eg i=
nsolvent) with its creditors almost certain to own the company after bankru=
ptcy. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Note that the =E2=80=9Cabsolute priority rule=E2=80=9D=
 in Chapter 11 bankruptcy means that for a security to get a recovery, any =
other security more senior in priority has to be paid off in full.</p></blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you agree with them, you could do a=
 trade. =E2=80=9CRevlon=E2=80=99s unsecured bonds trade at around 12 cents =
on the dollar,=E2=80=9D notes Bloomberg. You could[1]:</p><ol style=3D"list=
-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Short 1 million shares of Revlon stock; collect $8.1 m=
illion.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Buy $20 million face amoun=
t of Revlon bonds; pay about $2.4 million.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">You have $5.7 million left over; put that in the bank.[2]</li></ol=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the bankruptcy process will end with eith=
er (1) the stock getting something and the bonds getting paid in full or (2=
) the stock getting nothing and the bonds not getting paid in full. If the =
stock gets nothing, then you keep your $5.7 million, plus whatever recovery=
 the bonds get. If the stock gets something, then you end up with (1) the $=
5.7 million, plus (2) a $20 million recovery on your bonds, minus (3) whate=
ver the stock is worth. Revlon=E2=80=99s stock has traded no higher than $2=
4.02 since the start of 2020; if it ends up there =E2=80=94 up about 200% f=
rom yesterday=E2=80=99s close, up about 1,000% from the bankruptcy filing =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0then you <em>still</em> net about $1.7=C2=A0million.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This trade is not a bet that the price of Revlon s=
tock is <em>too high</em>.[3] Lots of people think it is but, sure, Hertz G=
lobal Holdings Inc. went bankrupt,=C2=A0its <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMTIvaWYteW91LXdhbnQtaGVydHotaGF2ZS1zb21l=
LWhlcnR6P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3N=
vdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB096aa993" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> stock</a> got <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMTIvaWYteW91LXdhbnQtaGVyd=
HotaGF2ZS1zb21lLWhlcnR6P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09=
ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ24=
9bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC096aa993" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> memed</a>, and =
then there ended up being <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR=
0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDUtMTIvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtdGhlLWhlcnR6LWdhbWJsZXJzLXdlcmUtcmlnaH=
Q_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB9208f5c9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a nice recovery for shareholders</a>, s=
o you never know.[4] But this trade is not a bet that Revlon won=E2=80=99t =
be valued above $4 billion. This trade is a bet that the price of Revlon st=
ock is=C2=A0<em>too high relative to the price of the bonds</em>. This is a=
 bet that the bankruptcy process works in a reasonably predictable way, and=
 the stock can=E2=80=99t have a huge recovery while the bonds have a tiny r=
ecovery. Just as a matter of arithmetic <em>one=C2=A0</em>of those prices i=
s wrong, and you can do this trade without a view on which one it is.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you probably can=E2=80=99t do this trade, or=
 at least, it is not nearly as good as I make it sound. The reason is that,=
 to do this trade, you need to short Revlon stock, which means that you nee=
d to borrow Revlon stock. That is, for one thing, hard to do: There is not =
all that much Revlon stock to borrow, in part because a lot of people want =
to short it and in part because almost 85% of it is owned by Revlon Chairma=
n Ronald Perelman. Also, because borrow is scarce, it is expensive: You wil=
l pay a large fee to borrow the stock, so=C2=A0your expected profits (or mo=
re) will go to your stock lenders. Also this is risky: If Revlon=E2=80=99s =
stock goes up <em>more</em>, you will have to pay more for borrow, and your=
 broker will ask you for more collateral, and if it goes up far enough you =
won=E2=80=99t have enough collateral and you=E2=80=99ll get blown out of th=
e trade at a huge loss.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, that will hap=
pen, because if you short the stock then meme-stock traders will buy it to =
try to squeeze you. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9yZXZsb24tc3RvY=
2stc3VyZ2VzLWFmdGVyLWJhbmtydXB0Y3ktZmlsaW5nLWFpZGVkLWJ5LWluZGl2aWR1YWwtaW52=
ZXN0b3JzLTExNjU1OTMwMzI1P21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB8b8003e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal notes</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More bearish bets have been placed on Revlon than near=
ly any other stock, according to Fintel, with about 37% of its shares avail=
able to the public currently sold short by investors who are betting they w=
ill fall.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Heavily shorted stocks can attrac=
t investors betting on a short squeeze, or a quick run up in share price th=
at forces short sellers to close their positions, boosting the shares.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That amount of short interest, plus a m=
arket capitalization of around $100 million as of its recent low, made Revl=
on=E2=80=99s stock =E2=80=9Ca perfect candidate for the most speculative re=
tail cohort,=E2=80=9D Vanda Research said in a note.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Revlon=E2=80=99s stock price, in some essential way,=
 makes no sense. Everyone can see that, and the market is generally in the =
business of noticing prices that make no sense and profitably correcting th=
em. But when a stock price gets=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>insanely high, it be=
comes too expensive and risky for anyone to correct.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Or we have talked a few times <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMTAvcmVkYm94LWlzLWZ1bi10by1tZW1lP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDA2MjMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBa5ae616d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> about Redbox Entertainment Inc.</a>, which is a tr=
uly wild meme-stock story. Redbox is a public company that agreed to be acq=
uired by Chicken Soup for the Soul Entertainment Inc. Each Redbox share wil=
l be exchanged for 0.087 Chicken Soup shares.=C2=A0The merger has not yet c=
losed, but I expect that it will; the controlling shareholders of Redbox ha=
ve agreed to vote for the deal, and I cannot imagine a regulatory impedimen=
t to merging these two random companies. There are no appraisal rights. You=
r Redbox shares will just turn into 0.087 Chicken Soup shares.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Redbox=E2=80=99s stock closed yesterday at $10.10 per =
share, up about 80% from where it was before the merger was signed. Chicken=
 Soup=E2=80=99s stock closed yesterday at $7.10 per share, down about 10%. =
When the merger closes, one share of Redbox (currently trading at $10.10) w=
ill turn into 0.087 shares of Chicken Soup (currently worth $0.62). There i=
s a super-obvious arbitrage:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padd=
ing-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Short=
 1 million shares of Redbox; collect $10.1 million.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">Buy 87,000 shares of Chicken Soup; pay $617,700.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now you have $9.5 million.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Wait.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Th=
e merger happens, the 1 million Redbox shares you=E2=80=99re short turn int=
o 87,000 Chicken Soup shares, you deliver your longs to close out your shor=
ts, and you keep $9.5 million of risk-free profit.</li></ol><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0this arbitrage is so obvious that people did it, and=
 then meme-stock buyers noticed that and said =E2=80=9Caha let=E2=80=99s sq=
ueeze the shorts,=E2=80=9D and they did. If you put this trade on on May 11=
, the day after the merger agreement was signed, when Redbox was at $3.20 a=
nd Chicken Soup was at $7.14, then as of today you have a mark-to-market lo=
ss of $6.9 million, even ignoring your borrow cost. (Also of course borrow =
is scarce and expensive.)=C2=A0A horrible trade! If you manage to hold on u=
ntil the merger closes you will get that back, but it will be very unpleasa=
nt.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have a solution to meme stocks,=
 but you don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0want to hear it.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Though, I mean: Do you think this is a problem? As a tidy-minded pe=
rson who grew up in equity derivatives, I find it unsettling; I experience =
a sort of aesthetic pain when stock prices are demonstrably wrong. But as a=
 guy who writes about weird financial stuff on the internet I like it just =
fine; more weird stuff to write about.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More=
 broadly, I suppose it is bad that some retail traders will lose money=C2=
=A0gambling on meme stocks, but on the other hand some retail traders will =
<em>make</em> money gambling on meme stocks (you could have bought Revlon a=
t $1.95 a week ago, after its bankruptcy filing, and sold it at a 300% prof=
it yesterday!), and maybe all of them are having a lot of fun and it=E2=80=
=99s fine. Some hedge funds will lose money doing entirely sensible arbitra=
ge trades, and I feel for them because that is unfair, but that is the life=
 they have chosen. At some margin meme-stock crazes probably allocate=C2=A0=
capital inefficiently, but on the other hand I doubt that Revlon will, like=
, go out and sell stock to raise money at these prices. (<a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDUtMTIvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtdGhlLWh=
lcnR6LWdhbWJsZXJzLXdlcmUtcmlnaHQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX2=
1lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjIzJnV0bV9jY=
W1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC9208f5c9" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Hertz tr=
ied that</a>, but got in trouble for it, and if it had succeeded it would h=
ave been a <em>good=C2=A0</em>allocation of capital. Other meme stocks, uh,=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28154643.280594/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvbW9u=
ZXktc3R1ZmYtYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhlLXBvcGNvcm4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMzIyX01PTkV=
ZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09Mj=
IwNjIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbc0ff647" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">do this</a>.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, a lot of people=
 don=E2=80=99t like the whole thing. They think that retail enthusiasm push=
ing up stock prices to obviously irrational levels is bad, because it under=
mines confidence in markets and allocates capital inefficiently and makes t=
he stock market feel like a casino and causes some people to lose money tha=
t they can=E2=80=99t afford to lose. Other people, I should say,=C2=A0<em>l=
ove=C2=A0</em>the whole thing; they think that there is something revolutio=
nary and democratic about taking financial power away from hedge funds doin=
g rational analysis and handing it to people having fun on Reddit.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you think it is bad, then there are two obvi=
ous approaches to fixing it:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padd=
ing-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Make =
memes harder to do, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Make arbitr=
age easier to do.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You occasionally se=
e calls for the first approach, like, =E2=80=9Ccriminally prosecute people =
for posting about stocks on Reddit=E2=80=9D or whatever. (Or <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMTcvYmUtY2FyZWZ1bC13aXR=
oLXlvdXItZmluYW5jaWFsLWluZmx1ZW5jZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjIzMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG=
1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA2MjMmdXRtX=
2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe1e927e4" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> at l=
east fire them</a>.) But there are obvious problems with this; to the exten=
t meme stocks are an emergent retail-trader phenomenon it is hard to regula=
te them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As for the second approach: In the=
 aftermath of the GameStop Corp. meme-stock event last year, the US Securit=
ies and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9zdGFmZi1yZXBvc=
nQtZXF1aXR5LW9wdGlvbnMtbWFya2V0LXN0cnVjdGlvbi1jb25kaXRpb25zLWVhcmx5LTIwMjEu=
cGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB07b1cb1d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">released a report</a> about=
 the causes of meme stocks and potential market reforms. The report describ=
ed limits to arbitrage in a sensible way:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The price surge in GME also raises questions of market efficienc=
y that relate to short selling. Staff have observed that it was unusually c=
ostly to borrow shares in GME. Academic research implicates constraints on =
short selling as a possible contributor to bubbles where stock prices rise =
above what may be justified by fundamentals.=C2=A0Such constraints on short=
 selling could arise from cost or from risk aversion. To the extent that Ga=
meStop was costly and risky to short, the reluctance to sell short could ha=
ve contributed to the run-up in prices and the subsequent steep decline.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is: Meme-stock bubbles=C2=
=A0are caused in part by constraints on short selling. But then the report=
=E2=80=99s conclusions were about more-or-less unrelated market-structure r=
eforms (reducing payment for order flow, restricting dark pools, etc.), and=
 about making life=C2=A0<em>harder=C2=A0</em>for short sellers: =E2=80=9CIm=
proved reporting of short sales would allow regulators to better track thes=
e dynamics.=E2=80=9D And in fact the SEC then=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28154643.280594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi=
9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0zMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB61131bb3" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">proposed new rules</a> that would require more short-sale reporting an=
d more=C2=A0<em>public=C2=A0</em>disclosure of short positions, in order to=
 =E2=80=9Cprovide the public and market participants with more visibility i=
nto the behavior of large short sellers.=E2=80=9D Which would make short sq=
ueezes easier. Which would make shorting riskier and=C2=A0deflating bubbles=
 harder.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine taking a differe=
nt approach. Make shorting=C2=A0<em>easier</em>, so that when stock prices =
become demonstrably irrational, a well-capitalized market participant could=
 take the other side and make them rational. Certainly nobody wants to hear=
 this, but if US securities laws=C2=A0<em>allowed naked short selling of st=
ocks </em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0if you had to post collateral to bet against stock=
s, but not negotiate with their holders to pay a fee to borrow them =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0then, uh,=C2=A0certain problems would become easier. If stocks wen=
t up too high, there would be incentives to bet against them, so they would=
n=E2=80=99t go up too high. That might make markets more rational.</p><tabl=
