crashes and that debt requires a 13% yield, then you will end up selling it=
 at 82 cents on the dollar, oops.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is in =
a sense a worse problem for the banks than it is for the buyers, though, be=
cause the buyers generally<em>=C2=A0intend=C2=A0</em>to own the companies f=
or a long time. If you sign a deal to buy a company and the market crashes =
before the deal closes, that is not=C2=A0<em>so=C2=A0</em>different from th=
e market crashing=C2=A0<em>after </em>the deal closes. You might get cold f=
eet, but you wanted to buy this company for some sort of long-term strategi=
c reason, and presumably the market cycle doesn=E2=80=99t change that too m=
uch.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the banks do=C2=A0not intend to ow=
n the buyout debt: They write commitment letters promising to buy the debt =
if no one else will, and then they get to work selling it to investors. The=
y are in the moving business, not the storage business, when it comes to th=
is sort of debt; if the crash had come just a bit later they=E2=80=99d have=
 sold it off at par and collected their fees. Of course then they=E2=80=99d=
 have moved on to do other deals, which would get hung when the crash event=
ually came.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspac=
ing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
